Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: @182172 On occasion the electrical contacts that the trains use to pass communications for door controls, power and brake, information systems, etc will not make contact properly.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: In these cases, detaching and reattaching is the approved process taken in line with our fleet 1/3

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: @182172 team's fault-finding instructions, and done under the instruction of maintenance staff and the fleet control manager.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: The train's fail-safe systems would not allow it to move in this situation, and if we could not resolve the problem, the train would be taken out of service.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: @182172 Safety is, and always will be, our first priority, and in this case protocols were followed correctly.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: Our fleet team will investigate using on-board monitoring systems as to what when wrong in this case and take appropriate action.
@SW_Help So wait a second.
Once a driver couples the train it's not protocol to test immediately, but to wait until the carriages are full of passengers to then couple?
That's your statement?

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: @182172 On more modern stock the train will undertake the necessary tests to confirm.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: With older trains, there is a "pull-away" test to confirm the trains are physically coupled together, but it is not always immediately apparent that the all of the 100+ contacts on the train 1/3

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: @182172 type in question are making suitable contact.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: Any one of these pins not making proper contact can result in the train not being able to move as part of fail-safe systems built in.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: As mentioned, more modern trains such as our 450 and 444 types have computer systems on board 2/3

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: @182172 which test each signal passing through the contacts to confirm that the train is attached both physically and electronically.

Utterance: @182172 No worries - I'm ex train-crew, so this is rather my specialist topic!

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: Appreciate that it seems a little antiquated, but it's all vetted and okayed by the safety bodies.

Speaker: SW_Help
Utterance: It's similar to the modern trains, where resolving problems can often come down to turning off the 1/2
